<br>
1) That the FGs would no longer be considered reservable by those whose sole purpose was to block people from going after Ragefire.<br>
<br>
2) That a camping cleric who spots Ragefire via feigned monk or Ranger tracking can step on the FG raid inorder to take down Ragefire.<br>
<br>
I would hope to see one or both of these in the FG rules section so that when rule 1 is violated a guild could just invoke rule 2.<br>
<br>
By putting these in the rules it would become more clear cut and someone who camps Ragefire is told he is SOL your 22 hours means nothing.<br>
<br>
It would keep FGs reservable to those that need training and leave the option for a camping cleric to take them down if Ragefire is up.<br>
<br>
More of these and other FGs abuses will only continue as people no longer respect a person camping a non-reservable mob and other don't view the FG's as reservable. If you want to keep FGs reservable try to think of rules that are not very complex and get them put in. Saying something is understood to be this way or that way only leads to grey areas and further arguments. <br>
<br>
Now as for my stating how long I was there in ooc I did that everytime one of your raiders claimed Ragefire. I could not get up and just leave (without training you) and I did not like having Ragefire being claimed by your raid being rubbed in my face. I did not log on about the same time to camp ragefire as Puma and Rinivi did. So while Puma did default a camp to Rinivi he never camped him for 20+hours seen Ragefire spawn the defaulted to Rinivi. Don't make his actions sound so noble.<br>
<br>
At least I am glad of one thing. It was Puma that got it. Why? We go back a long ways and were even in the same guild together at one point.<br>
